# **Abstract** {#abstract}

		The objective of this project is to explore and gain a deeper insight into adaptive cruise control and regenerative braking systems through the concept generation, design and simulation of these two controllers in Simulink. Adaptive cruise control (ACC) and regenerative braking are two systems in automotive vehicles that improve vehicle safety, performance, and user comfort. These systems are logic based, utilizing a logic controller to adjust the vehicle operating parameters and perform the specified functions of the system. 

In order to aid us in our endeavour, the vehicle dynamic model utilized in this project was based on an electric vehicle, specifically the Tesla Model S. This vehicle was used as the test platform for the designed controllers. Graphical representation of various parameters were intrinsically produced in Matlab-Simulink, in  order to gain a greater understanding on the fundamentals of automotive instrumentations and control systems. The simulation is designed with a lead car in front, travelling down a straight road. The lead car will have a set change in velocity over time—speeding up and slowing down—to trigger the regenerative braking and adaptive cruise control system of the vehicle model. The objective of the simulation is to gauge the designed vehicle dynamic model and maintain a desired travel distance from the lead car. In addition, the simulation will also showcase the brake signal split between regenerative braking and friction braking based on the conditions of the vehicle. To add, the adaptive cruise control shall operate in congruence by adjusting the throttle and brake outputs pertaining to the ego vehicle speed and distance between both vehicles. The simulation demonstrates the ability of the ego car's battery to be charged or discharged depending on the driving conditions met. Furthermore, the controller exhibiting regenerative braking exemplifies regenerative braking and hydraulic braking in various driving parameters such as vehicle speed, maximum AC torque achievable, and battery state of charge (SOC).

Challenges in the design process include the implementation of the designed controllers to the overall vehicle dynamic model, having the systems mesh together smoothly and encountering algebraic loops and linearization issues. 

The challenges insinuated by this project were successfully overcome, drastically increasing our comprehension upon the functionality behind ACC and regenerative braking. Furthermore our ability in plotting various controllers via simulink largely contributed in aggrandizing our knowledge of automotive instrumentation and controls, which is prominent in automotive engineering and highly relevant in our future careers.

# **Introduction** {#introduction}

This project focuses on the design of logic controllers in Simulink for automotive applications. Two logic controllers are explored, designed, and applied to a vehicle dynamic model in Simulink. The controllers serve as a means of altering the vehicle's operating parameters to achieve the basic functions of an adaptive cruise control system and a regenerative braking system. 

An adaptive cruise control system is a feature found in most modern automotive vehicles. It serves as both a safety feature and an ease of control feature for the driver. The system features the functions of a regular cruise control system with the added capabilities that allow for automatic application of the brakes and throttle based on the surrounding environment in which the vehicle travels. Active cruise control (ACC), is crucial as it immensely simplifies vehicle operation by relieving the drivers attention on the vehicle's speed, in turn, allowing operation behind slower vehicles with less mental effort. In addition, this improves road safety due to the greater distance between vehicles. Every adaptive cruise control system's primary function is to keep the speed constant, set by the driver's volition. This function can be referred to as the set speed controller, and is utilized once there is no lead vehicle present. This ultimately forces the driver to attain a speed value lower than the set speed. Therefore, it is highly effective if the vehicle in front of the car, which has an ACC accommodation, is travelling at a higher rate of speed. Essentially, the distinction between both adaptive cruise control and standard cruise control is the ACC’s ability to safely follow a vehicle in motion, which is traveling at a slower speed, as opposed to the cruising speed to which the driver has set \[1\]. Once the vehicle in front is travelling at a consistent speed, a car possessing ACC will travel behind it with the same speed, and produce a constant distance between both vehicles. This is primarily due to the vehicles both travelling around a consistent speed range, and the ACC’s ability to detect the rear end of the vehicle it is travelling behind. If the leading vehicle was to change direction (switch lanes or divert from the current path) and another vehicle becomes the relevant object under pursuit, the car equipped with ACC will automatically adjust without any driver input or intervention \[1\]. The adaptive cruise control system is intelligent, as it intrinsically adjusts the speed by electronically accelerating within certain limits pertaining to the engines management control system, and utilizes the braking system to obtain sufficient deceleration. This system utilizes a ranging sensor in order to detect vehicles driving in front, and to measure the distance and speed of the vehicle in pursuit. This sensor function can be addressed as the ACC-SCU (adaptive cruise control sensor and control unit), and is built into a single system. This ranging radar is proficient through the use of radio detection and range transmission of an electronic wave via antenna. The wave then bounces off an object present upon the radar's path and returns to the receiver of the system \[1\]. These radar signals are produced by electrically conductive materials present in modern vehicles today, and are ideal to be used as a distance measuring function. They are sufficient in hazardous weather conditions due to the use of longer wavelengths, as opposed to optical procedures.

A regenerative braking system converts the energy from the braking process of a vehicle into energy that can be used by the vehicle’s battery. This is achieved by capturing the kinetic energy of the vehicle's motion, routing it to a generator, which will then charge the battery. It is important that the system still performs its primary task of supplying sufficient friction force to the brakes while re-supplying charge back to the vehicle's battery. Regenerative braking is a crucial part of electric vehicles, as it improves the energy efficiency and vehicle range. During braking maneuvers, the electric motor will act as an electric generator by converting the kinetic energy of the vehicle, and transferring it into electric energy. This electric energy is stored in the battery for further use in future operations. Furthermore, studies have shown that 50% of the total brake energy generated by a vehicle can be recycled during the urban driving cycle \[2\]. This is common in vehicles operating at a low engine load, low exhaust gas temperature, and standard speed limit (around 50-60 km/h) \[2\]. In hybrid electric vehicles (HEVS) one of the greatest factors used to improve fuel efficiency is regenerative braking, as shown in the Toyota Prius, which accounts for up to a 35% of total energy efficiency improvement. \[3\] 

		The creation and integration of these systems is achieved through the application of logic controllers. The premise of a logic controller is to receive input data, from one part of the system, modify the signal and send it to actuators in the system to apply those changes and dynamically alter the operating parameters of that system. In the case of automotive applications, sensors across the vehicles collect data, which broadcast signals to various controllers utilising subsystems like the ECU. The signals will then adjust the vehicle’s operating parameters based on the criteria programmed by the vehicle manufacturer. The controllers will send instructions to the actuators throughout the vehicle, which would then be physically applied to change the operating conditions. For example, a speed and wheel position sensor will send data to a controller designed for emergency stability control. The controller is designed to apply changes to the vehicle’s throttle and braking systems in situations where hard braking and loss of stability is detected. The controller is programmed with these conditions in mind, so that when the operating parameters satisfy these conditions, the controller will send a signal to the appropriate actuators (brake caliper and throttle) in an attempt to assist the driver in stabilizing the vehicle and preventing loss of traction. 

		In this project, the adaptive cruise controller and regenerative braking systems were successfully designed and tested with various operating parameters in MATLAB/Simulink. The design, simulations and results of the two controllers are further discussed throughout this report. A brief introduction of the controller concepts will be discussed, followed by specific details pertaining to each subsystem. Finally, a discussion of the results will be presented with a conclusion to detail our success. 

# **Simulink Vehicle Model & Controllers**  {#simulink-vehicle-model-&-controllers}

## Vehicle Dynamic Model  {#vehicle-dynamic-model}

The vehicle dynamic model is based on an electric vehicle (EV) powered by a lithium iron phosphate battery. This specific model was loosely based on the operating parameters of the Tesla Model S. The model contains many subsystems that are essential to the vehicle’s operation. These subsystems include factors such as external forces, external moments, air temperature, 3 dimensional wind components, longitudinal parameters, and environmental parameters. The following table outlines the parameters defined in the vehicle body block. 

| Tesla Model S Standard Range |  |
| :---- | :---- |
| Vehicles total mass | 2135 Kg |
| Horizontal distance from CG to front axle | 1.46 m |
| Horizontal distance from CG to rear axle | 1.52 m |
| C.G Height above ground | 0.52 m |
| Frontal area | 2.32 m^2 |
| Air density | 1.202 kg/m^3 |
| Drag coefficient | 0.3 |
| Coefficient of Road/Tire adhesion | 0.015 |
| Tire radius | 0.3 m |
| Maximum torque | 600 Nm |
| Maximum Power | 750 Kw |
| Motor and Drive efficiency | 100 % |

Table1: Specification of Dynamic Vehicle Model

There are two ways to set up the vehicle dynamics. The first is to use the Vehicle Body block from the simscape library, provided by Simulink. We used the Vehicle with a Four-Speed Transmission example from the Matlab community to set up the vehicle shown in figure 1.![][image2]

Figure 1: Vehicle Dynamic with Simscape

This concept method has pros and cons. This method allows for a more detailed and accurate simulation. For example, this simulation can simulate variable slopes, variable wind speeds, road surface variations, and tire slip using magic formulas. The transfer function method cannot do this, but the transfer function block has a faster simulation test time. Instead, a second method would need a constant block, which represents disturbances and dynamic forces such as the road condition, road slope and grade, and air resistance.

### Motor System {#motor-system}

The motor configuration is also implemented in two different ways. The first is implemented with simscape, which has the disadvantage of continuously configuring with parameters in simscape due to the characteristics of the software. Therefore, the motor is also used with simscape, and the specifications are driven by a motor with a maximum power output of 750 KW and a torque value of 600 Nm as previously mentioned.

![][image3]

Figure 2: Motor System Design 

The motor block is named Motor & drive block shown in figure 2\. The motor block is easy to configure and is used for most motor simulations in simscape. Matlab states that this can be used as a brushless motor, similar to a permanent magnet synchronous motor (PMSM) so it was used for the model. PMSM utilize AC and DC motor characteristics. Therefore, we used this block as an AC motor. The battery is a 13.4V battery pack that was automatically implemented by Simulink. It is composed of eight 13.4V cells connected together in series.

### Lead Car {#lead-car}

To minimize our simulation time, we did not configure the vehicle’s dynamics for the lead car, but instead, used a drive cycle source block to load the simulated speed graph to use as a speed reference for the lead car. However, since the vehicle dynamics are not configured, the lead car does not look natural when visualized. The visualization was mostly used for reference and demonstration purposes.

## **Controllers** {#controllers}

### Adaptive Cruise Controller {#adaptive-cruise-controller}

![][image5]

Figure 4: Advanced Cruise System Controller

Figure 4 shows our adaptive cruise control system. There is a sensor block, a speed controller to adjust the speed, and a ‘speeddeicider’ block to determine desired and current distance and speed. For the sensor, we used the lead car distance- ego\_car\_distance to save our simulation speed, but for a more realistic implementation, we disabled detection if the lead car is more than 100 meters away.

In this concept, the linearization has already been done when implementing the vehicle dynamics, so the output of the vehicle dynamics model is velocity in meters per second. Furthermore, this method utilizes simscape, which does not require a transfer function. Therefore, we needed to implement a PID controller block and a signal block to divide the Acceleration and Braking. The result of this is shown in figure 5\.

![][image6]

Figure 5: PID Controller with Saturation Block

As shown in figure 5, the input dsp represents the desired speed. Subtracting the actual vehicle speed (ActuSP) from this will give the error value, which will be passed through the PID controller to give the adjusted value. The adjusted value will be divided by the acceleration (acc) and deceleration (dcc) values by the saturation block. Please note that the PID controller found in the cruise control subsystem was tuned to yield the following parameters:

Proportional value \= 0.1			Integral value \= 0.001  		 K=0.008

The parameter ‘K’ represents the velocity feed-forward gain. This adjusts the sensitivity of the output speed to change the cruise control speed, and is used to design a feed-forward control strategy that can improve the performance of the system when there are disturbances or changes in the input.

![][image7]

Figure 6: Throttle Delay Block

Figure 6 shows a block that calls Throttle delay. This is not necessary, but can be used for more realistic simulations and to prevent algebraic loops.

![][image8]

Figure 7: Speed and Distance Decider Block

The cruise controller block is a system implementation of several equations.

 

ad=(desired distance+current speed\*reaction time) 

Where another distance (ad) represents the stopping control distance.

The stopping control distance is an expression that calculates the stopping distance of the vehicle. It increases as desired distance, current speed, and reaction time increase. A saturation block is used to prevent the vehicle from going backwards by obtaining a value of below zero. The reaction time should be:  speeddeceleration , but due to time constraints of the project, we set it roughly to reaction time. 

Another definition of reaction time refers to the time required for the driver or vehicle to react. Limiter 1 is used to set the minimum acceptable distance required to maintain a desired distance from the lead car. 

The code in the Limiter 1 function block is found below:

| function ysat \= fcn(u,Limit) if u \<=Limit     u=u; end if u \>Limit     u=Limit; end ysat \= u; |
| :---- |

The equation below denotes the formula used to find the appropriate following distance:

Relative distance \= lead car position- ego car distance

Once the desired distance is calculated, the appropriate speed is calculated. The following expression represents the appropriate speed formula:

Desired speed=(relative distance-ad)reaction time

Another Limiter block is implemented, which prevents the vehicle speed value from exceeding the desired cruise speed value. 

The following code is found in the Limiter function block:

| function ysat \= fcn(u,Limit) if u \<=Limit     u=u; end if u \>Limit     u=Limit; end ysat \= u; |
| :---- |

The value obtained from this subsystem will feed into the speed controller.

### Regenerative Braking Controller {#regenerative-braking-controller}

The regenerative block/regenerative braking controller is a subsystem within the ‘ego car’ model of our vehicle dynamic system. This controller utilizes the following 4 inputs: State of Charge (SOC, %), Wheel Torque (WT, Nm), Brake Signal (Brk) and vehicle speed (spd). The outputs of this controller are friction brakes (Nm) and Regen brakes (Nm). The state of charge and wheel torque inputs are received from the motor systems block, while the brake signal input is received from the cruise controller system. The friction brake output is sent to the vehicle body block, in specific, to the double shoe brakes in the subsystem. The regenerative braking output is sent back to the motor system’s block to be subtracted from the throttle signal for the electric motor controller. 

![][image9]

Figure 9: Ego Car Model

The friction brake force signal output leads back to the vehicle body as ‘Brk’ signal 1, to be applied to the double-shoe (drum) brake as an actuation force, which effectively slows the vehicle. Please note that although the selected vehicle uses disk brakes, the system in our model uses drum brakes. This was done to simplify the model and reduce simulation time. 

![][image10]

Figure 10: Vehicle Body Model

The regenerative braking force leads back into the motor subsystem ‘Motorsystem’ as regenerative torque ‘Regen torque (Nm)’. The ‘Regen torque’ signal is subtracted from the throttle force signal. This is done to determine the direction of the motor, and to account for the delay between disengaging the throttle signal and engaging the brake signal. The signal remains positive when throttle force is greater than the regenerative torque, meaning the motor remains in the same direction. Given a positive signal, the battery is discharging, thus decreasing the state of charge. When the regenerative torque is greater than the throttle force, the difference between the signals is negative, which reverses the direction of the motor. Given a negative signal, the battery is in a charging state thus, increasing the state of charge.


![][image11]

Figure 11: Motor System

The regenerative braking controller is regulated by these three primary operating conditions:

- Maximum motor torque limit is 600 Nm  
- SOC is below 85%  
- Vehicle speed is greater than 0

When these conditions are satisfied, the controller sends all of the generated wheel torque to the regenerative brake system until the maximum motor torque limit is achieved. Once the limit has been reached, the rest of the wheel torque is directed towards the friction brakes. When any of these conditions are not satisfied, the controller routes all of the wheel torque towards the friction brakes and no regenerative braking occurs. 

These conditions were implemented into the system via 4 Matlab functions. The code for these Matlab functions are found in Appendix A1. 

![][image12]

Figure 12: Regenerative Brake System 

The wheel torque is multiplied by the brake signal so that the output gives a value when the brake signal is received from the cruise controller. This signal is an input to MATLAB ‘function 1’ from Appendix A1. The second input to this function is a SOC signal. The function outputs ‘y’ and ‘y2’ deliver data depending on the status of the inputs and if they meet a certain criteria. When the SOC is greater than 85%, all of the wheel torque input ‘u’ is routed to the output ‘y’, which is sent to the friction braking summation block. In this case, output ‘y2’ is equal to zero. When the SOC is less than 85%, then all of the wheel torque input ‘u’ is given to the output ‘y2’. In this case, output ‘y’ is equal to zero. 

The second function block verifies the value of the wheel torque input ‘u’ (from ‘y2’) and delivers the signal to the regenerative braking summation block, from output ‘y’, if the wheel torque is less than or equal to 600 Nm. Keep in mind that 600 Nm is the maximum motor torque limit. If 600 Nm is exceeded, the function reroutes the wheel torque value to be split between the friction brakes and regenerative brakes. 

The split occurs in the ‘WT split function’ block. when the block receives a signal, the output RB automatically sends 600 Nm of wheel torque to the regenerative brake summation block. The difference between the received signal and 600 Nm is then sent to the friction brake summation block through the FB output. 

The final matlab function, found after the ‘regen brakes’ summation block, verifies that the vehicle is going at a non-zero speed. It has an input of a speed signal (spd) and torque signal (u). If the speed is greater than zero, the signal will pass to become regenerative torque. If the value is equal to or less than zero, then the regenerative braking will not occur.  


Integration & Tuning 

The tuning process involved adjusting various parameters to finetune the controller’s output to a desired value. The PID controller found in the adaptive cruise controller was tuned via the Transfer Function Based (PID Tuner App) method. Please note that the PID controller in this subsystem was tuned to yield the following parameters: 

Proportional value \= 0.4			Integral value \= 0.001  		 K=0.001

These values reduce the gain of the desired speed (dsp). Given these selected parameters, the response time and transient behavior of these values were adjusted in the PID Tuner, to achieve the desired block response which is to have a stable response with minimal overshoot as shown below. This is critical in the design of the controller as an unstable PID response can result in a decrease in efficiency and functionality. With increased failures and detriments, the longevity of the system and connected physical components will be shorter than expected. (i.e vehicle actuators, brakes, throttle, AC motor and battery).

# **Results & Discussion** {#results-&-discussion}

## Simulink Simulation  {#simulink-simulation}

![][image17]

Figure 16: Vehicle Dynamic Scope

The 3 graphs shown in figure 16 plot acceleration, deceleration and the relative distance of the ego car to the lead car. These are the results plotted against time after running the simulation. It can be observed that between the same time intervals, change in relative distance and acceleration becomes zero. In addition, deceleration also increases at a linear rate, showing the exact moment when the adaptive cruise controller is activated to maintain the desired distance from the lead vehicle. This shows that the cruise controller achieved the required action and application of slowing down the vehicle to maintain the desired distance from the lead vehicle. Between 1200 and 2000 seconds, the acceleration and velocity of the vehicle slowly converges to zero. It is important to note that the wind force must always be applied to the model. This resistance slowly pushes the car backwards, and may interfere with the desired distance between the vehicles. The solution is to adjust P by a marginal amount, so that the car applies the brakes and stops within 10 meters of the target distance. The value of P was found to be best at 0.1, whereas a smaller value would yield an inaccurate result. 

![][image18]

Figure 17: Vehicle Speed Plot

The plot shown in figure 17 displays the speed of the ego vehicle  versus that of the lead car. Both speeds are synchronized, indicating that the system was successful in maintaining the desired distance between the lead car. The system was able to reach and match the speed of the lead car to adapt and reduce error.

 ![][image19]

figure 18: Vehicle Distance Plot

	The plot shown in figure 18 displays the relative distance of the lead car and the ego vehicle. It is evident that each curve is identical, with two offset parameters. The horizontal offset is attributed to the time delay in the response. The vertical offset represents the distance between the lead car and the ego vehicle. As previously stated, all of the points along each curve are separated by a somewhat constant value. This constant distance shows the high accuracy that our designed controller has achieved.

In the first plot, we can see that the SOC is decreasing with many fluctuations, indicating that the battery is discharging and charging as the vehicle speed varies. The second plot re-emphasizes the effect of the regenerative braking system. The rate of charge is negative when the vehicle is discharging the battery during acceleration maneuvers. The rate of charge is positive when the vehicle is charging the battery during deceleration and braking maneuvers. 

# **Conclusion**  {#conclusion}

The purpose of this project was to study, design and simulate a cruise controller and a regenerative braking controller, to ultimately achieve a comprehensive understanding of logic controller applications and their crucial role within automotive instrumentation and controls. This objective was successfully fulfilled with the complete build of a vehicle dynamic model and full development of two controllers, for that model, using the Simulink software. The controllers were put to the test in a simulation in which the ego car travelled behind a lead car that varied its speed. This was done to test the effectiveness of the controllers in adjusting operating parameters to the changing operational conditions. The simulation demonstrated that the ego car was successful in maintaining a desired distance from the lead car, as the adaptive cruise controller was able to successfully adjust the throttle & brake outputs using ego vehicle speed and front vehicle distance as inputs. The simulation also showed that the ego car’s battery was charged and discharged based on the operating status of the vehicle. The regenerative brake controller successfully split the brake signal to regenerative braking and friction braking in accordance to several operating conditions including vehicle speed, AC motor torque limit and battery SOC. 

Throughout this project, a deeper understanding of Simulink and control system design was developed through its use and application. Various blocks were used and their parameters were adjusted to achieve the functionality required in the design. Many scopes were placed, in specific areas of the design, to retrieve data and verify that the design was providing the desired outputs and changes in operating parameters. This demonstrated a good understanding of the system, being able to know where to appropriately place the scope, providing further insight on how to take full advantage of the tools made available in Simulink. MATLAB functions were used to write code, which set the operating conditions and adjusted the signals in accordance to the vehicle status. PID tuning was performed to obtain the optimal proportional and integral value to ensure the PI response was stable. Unreal Engine visualization tools built into Simulink were discovered and used to provide a strong visual representation of the system, allowing for easier comprehension of the designed system’s effect on the overall vehicle, and visual proof  that the controllers were successful in altering the vehicle operating parameters to achieve the set out functions of the regenerative braking and adaptive cruise control systems. Finally, the Simulink model was compiled and converted into C code. 

Overall, this project was an extension to the material learned in the classes and labs, and was an opportunity to apply the course material. The project was a success, garnering crucial experience and further insight into the process of automotive controller design.
